 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are given a piece of user text input. Your task is to classify this text into exactly one of the following functional domain categories:\n\nalarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS FOR CLASSIFICATION:\n\n1. Carefully read the full user input and determine their PRIMARY intent. Do not rely solely on keywords—consider domain-specific nuances and real user expectations.\n\n2. Use the most appropriate, specific category based on user intent. For each category, consider the following domain-specific rules and guidance:\n\n   - **Alarm-related:**\n     - 'alarm_set': Set, create, or activate an alarm or alert for a specific time or event EXCLUDING contextual real-world conditions (e.g., \"Set an alarm for 6 AM\"). \n     - 'alarm_query': Requesting information about existing or upcoming alarms.\n   \n   - **Weather-related:**\n     - 'weather_query': Any request involving weather conditions, forecasts, temperatures, or alerts tied to environmental changes (e.g., \"alert me when the outside temperature reaches sixty eight degrees\" should be 'weather_query', NOT 'alarm_set').\n   \n   - **Calendar-related:**\n     - 'calendar_query': Asking about events, appointments, schedules, or availability.\n     - 'calendar_set': Creating or adding a new event.\n     - 'calendar_remove': Deleting or removing an event.\n   \n   - **Music and Entertainment:**\n     - 'play_music': Requests to play music in general, or from specific genres, artists, or songs (e.g., \"play jazz,\" \"play Taylor Swift\").\n     - 'play_radio': Requests to play radio stations, broadcast shows, or any radio-like national or entertainment show—even if performances are musical in nature (e.g., \"play for me american idol show\" → 'play_radio').\n     - 'music_query': General queries about music or musical content that does NOT request to actually play anything.\n     - 'news_query': Requests for news updates or information.\n     - 'play_audiobook', 'play_podcasts': As implied, for audiobooks or podcasts respectively.\n\n   - **Other functional domains:**\n     - 'iot_hue_lightoff': Commands to control smart lights (e.g., turning off Hue lights).\n     - 'cooking_recipe': Requests for recipes or cooking instructions.\n     - 'datetime_query': Asking for the current date or time.\n     - **Lists and tasks:**\n       - 'lists_createoradd': Adding to, creating, or expanding a list/task.\n       - 'lists_query': Requesting to view or list contents of a list/task.\n       - 'lists_remove': Removing items from a list/task.\n     - **Email:**\n       - 'email_query': Asking about inbox contents or existing emails.\n       - 'email_sendemail': Requests to send or compose an email.\n     - 'recommendation_events'/'recommendation_locations': Requests for suggestions on events or places.\n     - 'social_post': Requests to create or post on social media.\n     - 'takeaway_order': Requests to order food for takeaway.\n     - 'transport_query': Queries about transportation, directions, or rides.\n\n   - **Question Answering:**\n     - Use qa_* categories as follows:\n       - 'qa_currency': Currency rate or exchange information.\n       - 'qa_definition': Definitions or meanings of terms.\n       - 'qa_factoid': Simple, factual information requests.\n       - 'qa_stock': Stock/financial instrument queries.\n\n   - **General/Fun/Unusual:**\n     - 'general_quirky': For fun, quirky, playful, or unusual requests that do not fit any other category.\n\n3. DO NOT output anything other than the exact single category label from the provided list. DO NOT provide explanations.\n\n4. Always prefer 'weather_query' IF the query relates to weather information or triggers/alerts based on weather changes, even if the wording suggests an 'alarm' or 'alert'. Do not confuse environmental alert requests (e.g., \"alert me when temperature...\") with time-based alarms—use 'weather_query' for the former.\n\n5. Pay attention to all provided special rules and category boundaries, especially as some user requests may crosscut general language patterns.\n\nYour output should be the correct category label—nothing else."
 },
